d": false, "mention": "zebrafish", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9330744743347168, "span": {"begin": 389, "end": 398}}, {"id": ["mesh:C016531"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "11-KT", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9957373142242432, "span": {"begin": 452, "end": 457}}, {"id": ["mesh:C016531"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "11-KT", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9865368008613586, "span": {"begin": 617, "end": 622}}, {"id": ["CL:0000019"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "sperm", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7512059807777405, "span": {"begin": 675, "end": 680}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "teleost", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.7440711855888367, "span": {"begin": 695, "end": 702}}, {"id": ["mesh:C016531"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "11-KT", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.953698992729187, "span": {"begin": 723, "end": 728}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:7937"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Japanese eel", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.8628357648849487, "span": {"begin": 784, "end": 796}}, {"id": ["mesh:C016531"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "11-KT", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9970400929450989, "span": {"begin": 856, "end": 861}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Sertoli cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8503259420394897, "span": {"begin": 922, "end": 935}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3625"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "activin B", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9968159794807434, "span": {"begin": 940, "end": 949}}, {"id": ["mesh:C016531"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "11-KT", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9944391250610352, "span": {"begin": 1044, "end": 1049}}, {"id": ["CL:0000019"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "sperm", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7089511752128601, "span": {"begin": 1092, "end": 1097}}], "text": "Androgens are critical for maintaining the normal male reproductive system (Tang, H., et al. 2018). Of these androgens, 11-KT has been identified as the most important in teleost fish (Borg, B. 1994). 11-KT is produced by the cyp11c1 encoded enzyme, 11&szlig;-hydroxylase (Zheng, et al. 2020). 11-KT has been shown to bind to the androgen receptor with similar affinity as testosterone in zebrafish (Jorgensen, et al. 2007). It is well documented that 11-KT is involved in spermatogenesis, spermiation, male secondary sexual characteristics, and breeding behaviors (Geraudie, P. et al. 2010; Amer, M.A. et al. 2001). 11-KT is needed for the inducement of spermatogenesis and sperm production in teleost fish, with 10 ng/ml 11-KT being sufficient to induce full spermatogenesis in the Japanese eel (Miura, C. and T. Miura 2011). The mechanism through which 11-KT induces spermatogenesis is believed to be via activation of Sertoli cells and activin B (Miura et al. 2011; Miura et al. 2001; Sales, C.F., et al. 2020; Cavaco J.E.B., et al. 1998). 11-KT is not responsible for the acquisition of sperm motility in salmonids (Miura, et al. 1992).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:26:03 +0000 2026"}